.TH CHKBOUNCE 8 "2026\-05\-05" "chkbounce" "System Administration Utilities"
.
.SH NAME
chkbounce \- network packet reachability tester
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B chkbounce
.B \-s
.RB [ \-p
.IR port ]
.RB [ \-\-timeout= seconds ]
.
.br
.B chkbounce
.B \-c
.I server
.RB [ \-p
.IR port ]
.RB [ \-i [ types ]]
.RB [ \-t [ ports ]]
.RB [ \-u [ ports ]]
.RB [ \-\-timeout= seconds ]
.RB [ \-o
.IR file ]
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B chkbounce
determines which types of network traffic can traverse the path between two
hosts.
It operates in a client/server model: the server runs persistently on the
target machine, and clients connect to it over a TCP control channel to
negotiate and execute a sequence of probes.
For each probe the server opens a single socket immediately before the client
fires the packet, then reports the result back over the control channel.
.PP
Supported probe types are:
.TP
.B ICMP
Raw ICMP packets with a specified type number (0\(en255).
.TP
.B TCP
TCP connection attempts to specified port numbers.
.TP
.B UDP
UDP datagrams sent to specified port numbers.
.PP
Both the client and the server must be run with root privileges (or
.BR CAP_NET_RAW )
because ICMP probing requires a raw socket.
.
.SH MODES
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-server
Run in server mode.
The server binds to the control port, then loops on
.BR accept (2),
handling one client session at a time.
It runs until interrupted with
.BR Ctrl\-C .
.TP
.BI \-c " server" "\fR,\fP \-\-client"
Run in client mode.
.I server
is the hostname or dotted\-decimal IPv4 address of the machine running
.BR chkbounce\ \-s .
Hostnames are resolved via DNS before connecting.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-p " port" "\fR,\fP \-\-port=" port
TCP port number used for the control channel on both sides.
Must match between client and server.
Default:
.BR 1234 .
.TP
.BI \-\-timeout= seconds
Per\-probe timeout in seconds.
The server waits up to this long for each probe packet to arrive before
reporting the probe as not received.
Default:
.BR 2 .
.TP
.RB [ \-i [ types ]] ", [" \-\-icmp [= types ]]
Enable ICMP probes.
.I types
is a range list (see
.BR "RANGE SYNTAX"
below) of ICMP type numbers in the range 0\(en255.
If
.I types
is omitted, all 256 types (0\(en255) are probed.
.TP
.RB [ \-t [ ports ]] ", [" \-\-tcp [= ports ]]
Enable TCP probes.
.I ports
is a range list of port numbers.
If
.I ports
is omitted, the default set is used:
.BR "22, 80, 443, 8080, 8443" .
.TP
.RB [ \-u [ ports ]] ", [" \-\-udp [= ports ]]
Enable UDP probes.
.I ports
is a range list of port numbers.
If
.I ports
is omitted, the default set is used:
.BR "53, 123, 161" .
.TP
.BI \-o " file" "\fR,\fP \-\-output=" file
Write the final report to
.I file
in addition to printing it to standard output.
The file is created if it does not exist and overwritten if it does.
Progress and connection messages are not written to the file.
.PP
If none of
.BR \-i ,
.BR \-t ,
or
.B \-u
is specified, the client probes all three protocols using their default lists
(equivalent to supplying
.B \-i \-t \-u
with no arguments).
.
.SH RANGE SYNTAX
Range lists are composed of comma\-separated values and inclusive
.IB start \- end
ranges.
No spaces are allowed within a range list.
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.TP
.B 80
The single port 80.
.TP
.B 22,80,443
Ports 22, 80, and 443.
.TP
.B 8080\-8090
Ports 8080 through 8090 inclusive.
.TP
.B 22,25\-30,80,443
Ports 22, 25, 26, 27, 28, 29, 30, 80, and 443.
.TP
.B 0,3,8\-11,255
ICMP types 0, 3, 8, 9, 10, 11, and 255.
.RE
.PP
.B Important:
When using short options
.RB ( \-t ,
.BR \-u ,
.BR \-i )
with an explicit range list, the list must immediately follow the flag with
.B no intervening space:
.PP
.RS
.nf
\-t80,443      # correct
\-\-tcp=80,443  # correct
\-t 80,443     # WRONG \(em treated as \-t (defaults) plus stray argument
.fi
.RE
.
.SH PROTOCOL
The client and server communicate over a framed binary protocol on the TCP
control channel.
Each message consists of a one\-byte type field, a four\-byte big\-endian
payload length, and the payload.
.PP
The session proceeds as follows:
.RS
.IP 1. 4
The client connects to the server's control port.
.IP 2.
The client sends a
.I negotiate
message listing every probe it intends to run.
.IP 3.
The server replies
.IR ready .
No probe sockets are opened at this stage.
.IP 4.
For each probe in order:
.RS
.IP a. 4
Client \(-> Server:
.I probe\-next
(protocol, port/type number).
.IP b.
Server opens the probe socket
.RI ( listen (2)
for TCP,
.IR bind (2)
for UDP, or reuses the per\-session raw socket for ICMP).
.IP c.
Server \(-> Client:
.IR probe\-go .
.IP d.
Client sends the probe packet.
.IP e.
Server waits up to
.B \-\-timeout
seconds.
If the probe arrives, it reports
.I received
immediately.
Otherwise it reports
.I not\-received
after the timeout.
Server \(-> Client:
.IR probe\-result .
.IP f.
For TCP and UDP the per\-probe socket is closed.
.RE
.IP 5.
Client sends
.IR done .
Server closes the client connection and returns to
.BR accept (2).
.RE
.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Start the server on the default control port
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-s
.fi
.SS Start the server on port 5000 with a 5\-second timeout
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-s \-p 5000 \-\-timeout=5
.fi
.SS Probe all three protocols using defaults
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-c server.example.com
.fi
.SS Probe ICMP only (all 256 types)
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-c 192.168.1.50 \-i
.fi
.SS Probe specific ICMP types
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-c 192.168.1.50 \-i0,3,8,11
.fi
.SS Probe TCP on a mix of individual ports and a range
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-c 192.168.1.50 \-t22,80,443,8080\-8090
.fi
.SS Probe UDP
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-c 192.168.1.50 \-u53,67\-69,123,161
.fi
.SS Combine protocols with a custom control port and timeout
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-c firewall.internal \-p 5000 \-\-timeout=3 \e
               \-i0,3,8 \-t22,80,443 \-u53,123
.fi
.SS Save the report to a file
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-c 192.168.1.50 \-t22,80,443 \-\-output=report.txt
.fi
.SS Combine all options including output file
.nf
sudo chkbounce \-c firewall.internal \-p 5000 \-\-timeout=3 \e
               \-i0,3,8 \-t22,80,443 \-u53,123 \-\-output=/tmp/fw\-report.txt
.fi
.SS Loopback test (client and server on the same machine)
.nf
# Terminal 1
sudo chkbounce \-s

# Terminal 2
sudo chkbounce \-c 127.0.0.1 \-t80,443 \-u53
.fi
.
.SH NOTES
.TP
.B IPv4 only
IPv6 is not currently supported.
.TP
.B One client at a time
The server is single\-threaded and handles one client session at a time.
A second client must wait for the current session to complete.
.TP
.B Privileged ports
Binding TCP or UDP ports below 1024 on the server requires root.
If the server cannot bind a requested port, that probe is reported as
.I not received
and the session continues.
.TP
.B NAT
When the client is behind NAT, the server sees the NAT gateway's address
rather than the client's private address.
The server uses the control\-channel source IP to filter ICMP and UDP probes;
a NAT mismatch can cause false
.I not received
results for those protocols.
TCP probes are unaffected because the NAT gateway rewrites the source address
consistently.
.TP
.B Host firewalls
A firewall on the server machine (e.g.\&
.BR iptables (8),
.BR nftables (8))
may drop probe packets before they reach the listening socket, producing
false
.I not received
results even when the network path itself is clear.
.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR ping (8),
.BR traceroute (8),
.BR nmap (1),
.BR iptables (8),
.BR nftables (8),
.BR raw (7),
.BR socket (7)
.
